
[1]fougade

   FOUG'ADE, n. [L. focus.]

   In the art of war, a little mine, in the form of a well, 8 or 10 feet
   wide, and 10 or 12 deep, dug under some work, fortification or post,
   charged with sacks of powder and covered with stones or earth, for
   destroying the works by explosion.
